segments.text: Karen Rossell on April the 6th at Texas A&M University concerning reconnaissance missions flown over Southeast Asia.
How many missions did you fly?
Did you volunteer or were you sent there?
I volunteered.
Volunteered to go?
When did you fly these missions and where?
I flew from January
of 1973 until about mid-November of 1973.
And I flew in all over South Vietnam, all over Laos, and all over Cambodia.
And I flew a few training missions over Thailand.
What was the purpose of your missions during this time period?
Intelligence gathering.
Primarily
with pictures, although we also used a few other sensors like infrared and visual reconnaissance.
What were you trying to pick up for the intelligence?
What were you trying to take pictures of?
Well, several things.
For one thing, we did bomb damage assessment, BDA if you will, of targets that had been struck by various means, but primarily
targets that had been struck by air.
We also did target development.

That is, we would run or take pictures or do visual reconnaissance primarily of roads on the Ho Chi Minh Trail, which is basically through Laos, a system of roads through Laos where the North Vietnamese sent troops and supplies down to South Vietnam.
Although we also ran several other roads.
We looked at a lot of other roads all over Southeast Asia just to see what was going on on those roads and pick out targets for later bombing or what have you.
Did you have any other involvement in Southeast Asia prior to these missions?
Any type of at-home involvement, like maybe doing stuff that like relay stuff as opposed to being actually over there?
No.
I guess not.
No.
What were your feelings on the war and the United States' involvement in the war?
And did it change over time?
Did you have like a certain opinion when you first, you know, like in the early 60s and then as time progressed, did your opinion change on it?
I'd say my opinion remained fairly consistent from about 1960...
four up until 75 my feelings were relatively stable and I primarily thought that we were screwing up pretty badly by not taking a tougher stance, i.e.
bombing North Vietnam heavily and not restricting ourselves so much.
What kind of information were you given as to why you were there and what was going on there?
Were you well informed as to exactly why you were going over there, or was it kind of like you were just going and you really didn't know exactly what your mission was at the time?
Well, I knew exactly what I was going to do.
I was well informed, I guess, from my little piece of the pie, realizing, of course, I was only 29 years old and...
a young captain, so I was not one of the major planners, nor a major leader, but I knew exactly what I was going to have to do, and there were very few surprises to me.
So you were well informed of what the situation was over there?
Because in our class we've learned that a lot of stuff was kept from the people in the United States, a lot of stuff was
I guess like the Gulf of Tonkin resolution stuff, stuff wasn't told the way it actually happened.
It was kind of masked.
Were they more informative with you on stuff like that?
Well, I'm not sure I know what you mean by that.
I'm not sure I know what you're talking about with the Gulf of Tonkin resolution.
They said that some of the stuff was told to the public that it was happening at a more escalated rate than it actually was.
the United States may not have needed to react as quickly because things weren't actually happening.
They kind of upscaled it to get the American people behind it.
Well, the Gulf of Tonkin resolution was in the mid-60s somewhere.
I believe it was about 63 or 64, wasn't it?
Yeah, it was pretty early.
And when I went over there, it was almost 10 years later.
And for me to give an accurate assessment of...
of our public affairs, the military's public relations with the press, I can't evaluate that because I really don't know.
I can tell you that I felt fairly well informed.
That's not to suggest, however, that I knew or understood everything that was going on in all of those countries because it was a very complicated war.
What kind of preparatory information were you given before these missions?
Well, it sort of depended on where I was going and what I was doing.
We flew a lot of different tactics while I was there.
In one year, things changed a lot and we did a lot of different kinds of things and we flew in several different countries.
So it depended on where we were going.
But essentially, prior to every mission,

got an intelligence briefing by typically a fairly young intelligence officer on what the situation was, where we were going to be going, and then an overview of what was going on all over Southeast Asia.
So in general, I felt a pretty good idea of what was going on.
Does that answer your question?
Yeah.
Were you given any type of cultural background
into the Southeast Asian culture before you went?
Not in any great detail except to the extent of how to deal with captors in the event of coming to POW.
Okay, that's the next question.
What would happen if you were shot down and taken prisoner and how are you prepared for this event?
as well prepared as one could be at the time when I went over there because by that time we had a lot of intelligence on how the POWs were being treated and what was going on.
So I was, I felt like I was well prepared as far as knowing what to expect when I became a POW.
I knew that.
What kind of things did they tell you to expect?
Well, that's a wide-ranging question.
But in general, fairly rough treatment by the general population if you were not picked up by regular troops.
But if you were picked up by civilians, you could expect very rough treatment, perhaps not to survive.
If you were picked up by regular military troops, you could expect to get a little bit better treatment and to initially start out with
intense interrogation, poor treatment to include physical abuse.
And then shortly after that, isolation for a period of time, varying depending on where you were and what was going on.
It could vary how long you'd be in isolation.
And then ultimately to rejoin and be with other prisoners.
And that's just a very short synopsis, but we felt like we were fairly well, or I felt like I was fairly well prepared.
And since I was in a high-threat aircraft, the RF-4, I expected I had a better chance of being shot down than a lot of other people over there.
So I more or less expected it to happen.
Were these missions kept from the general public?
By the way, there was another problem.
Excuse me.
Another problem developed while I was there that might be interesting.
The POWs were released in March of 1973.
So I was still flying until November.
So we had some difficulty there.
We were not certain.
Our rules were vague on what was going to happen if we got shot down.
because we were still flying combat missions, and this is not commonly known, I guess.
We were still flying a lot of combat missions after the POWs were released, and we weren't real sure what was going to happen to us if we got shot down.
In other words, who was going to come help us was a question, which caused us a little bit of concern.
We were not
Concerned over whether you'd be recognized for actually being there?
No, concerned over whether or not we would be, well, let's see, how can I say this?

Whether or not we'd get a good strong attempt at a rescue, let's put it that way, a search and error rescue, because the POWs had already been released and it was kind of, we weren't real sure what the rules were going to be, that's the best way to put it.
We more or less expected Air America to help us.
So it wasn't common public knowledge that you were there after the POWs were released?
Well, I'm not sure if it was or not.
I guess it probably wasn't.
I don't think a lot of people realize that there was still an air war going on, or that is, U.S. air was being used extensively after the POWs had been released, at least all through the year of 73.
Were you able to tell your family about these missions, or were they, I guess if they were intelligence, they were...

probably I I don't I didn't I don't know I guess I could have but I didn't think that they didn't tell them I didn't think they'd understand okay do you know how these pictures were to be used I mean what they what exactly I guess they were used to to find targets and did I know how they were going to be used yes I knew how they were going to be used okay uh I was uh well depending on what they
If it was BDA, it was going to be used to determine how much damage was done to a target and whether or not it had to be struck again.
And if I was searching for targets, I knew that if I found them, that we would ultimately go back and hit them, probably.
And that was the concept.
From what you saw, were there any different policies that could have been followed to keep communism out of Southeast Asia besides the further bombing of the North?
You already said that earlier, but...
Any policies that you thought that the government could have taken to, I guess, to cause a winning situation?
Well, I don't really, I don't think I feel qualified to answer that question, although I'll give you a sarcastic answer.
Yeah, we could have chosen the other side.
And that's a theory that's been put forth before, is we could have taken the other side.
We could have taken Ho Chi Minh's side and perhaps kept communism out of there that way.
What do you think of the role of the press in Southeast Asia?
I know that a lot of people say that they think that the press lost the war.
What's your opinion on that?
No, I don't think it was the press.
No, I don't think the press was a factor in causing the war to be lost.
I don't think the war...
I'm not sure I even agree that the war was lost.
But I don't think the press had that much to do with it.
I think the administrations who were running the war

screwed it up and could have handled the press better um what do you think of the role the cia had what kind of involvement the cia had in southeast asia do you know of anything again i'm not a i'm not i'm not sure i'm qualified to answer that uh what do i think of the cia's role or yeah what do you i mean do you think they had a big role or that maybe their role could have been bigger or that
they could have done something else or done less?
Well, they had a pretty big role, and I'm not sure exactly how big.
I know that they were participants.
I saw them participate, especially with airplanes in Air America.
But I don't feel qualified to answer that.
I don't think I know.
What do you know about Air America?
Personally, I've never heard anything about it until in this class that I'm taking.
What kind of role did they have?
What did they do?
Well, they essentially did things that the military could not do.
They flew a lot of dangerous missions over there that we didn't or would not fly or could not fly.
They landed
in places where we couldn't go.
They flew unmarked airplanes, and they were an airline, you know, and technically, I guess, not representing or the theory was that they were not representing the U.S. government.
What was the purpose of them being there?

Because I know that in the movie that they had on Air America, they had that they were dropping, I know that that was an awful movie, but they were dropping food and stuff like that over Laos and Cambodia mostly.
Well, they did a lot of that.
They operated a lot in Laos, I know that.
Was that the major purpose of their mission, was to feed the people?
Well, that was one of the missions.
But I mean, they weren't there to help the Pathet Lao or the communist Laos take over the country, I can tell you that.
They were on our side, our side being against communism.
And that's an oversimplification, I realize, but I really don't know any other way to say it.
And as far as getting into detail about their operations, I can't, because I just don't know that much about it.
What do you think of Jane Fonda's role in Southeast Asia, or what kind of effect she had?
Well, I kind of hate to dignify Jane Fonda by even discussing her.
I think that it's unfortunate that the press would have given her the time that they did.
in the public eye.
And I would join with all the POWs and most of the military people who were around during that era in despising what she stood for and what she represented.
And I guess it remains a fairly emotional issue with me as it does with
most other people who were in the military at that time.
She had an impact, and she did, and you can ask most of the POWs, she caused problems for them by going to North Vietnam.

Do you think that she was, because I've heard that there were other people that had the same view, that she got more press than, because she was already famous, that she got more press than other people.
Do you know anything about any other people that were involved in that, or in her same mission for going over there and her
Well, I'm sure that there were others.
I don't know who they were, and I don't remember.
I mean, that's been so many years ago now, and I don't remember who they were.
I'm sure there were others, but she's the one who sticks out in my mind and most other folks' minds, and she's the one who's remembered.
And she got so much press.
She got so much press.
Okay, that's it.
Thank you.
